<Docs title="Manifest Format" description="The normative grammar of a .life manifest head — the strict subset, the frozen waist, and the three config-carrying graph maps of format epoch 2 (life: 1.0).">
  <h1>Manifest format</h1>
  <p class="lead">The normative grammar of a <code>.life</code> manifest head — format <strong>epoch&nbsp;2</strong> (<code>life: 1.0</code>). The reference implementation is the engine's own parser (<code>kernel/lib/grammar.js</code> + <code>kernel/lib/parser.js</code>, shipped as the <a href="/registry?q=life">life</a> engine); conformance is defined by the fixture set below, not by what any YAML library tolerates. Key words <strong>MUST</strong>, <strong>SHOULD</strong>, and <strong>MAY</strong> are used as in RFC&nbsp;2119.</p>

  <h2>Shape of a <code>.life</code> file</h2>
  <p>A <code>.life</code> file is a <strong>head</strong> and a <strong>body</strong>, separated by the first line that is exactly <code>---</code>. The head is the machine surface this document specifies. The body is free-form Markdown — the cell's README, read first by any human or agent that lands there — and this spec places <strong>no</strong> constraint on it. A file with no <code>---</code> separator is all head.</p>

  <h2>The whole model in one breath</h2>
  <p>A head is the <strong>waist</strong> — exactly what the engine must understand before any gene loads — plus <code>meta:</code>. Nothing else may appear at the top level. The three graph keys (<code>imports:</code>, <code>requires:</code>, <code>provides:</code>) share one shape: <strong>maps whose keys are edges the engine reads, and whose values are opaque config — any shape: map, scalar, list, or empty — read only by the party at the other end of the edge.</strong> A gene's config rides its <code>imports:</code> entry; a capability's provisioning config rides its <code>requires:</code> entry; a provider's contract rides its <code>provides:</code> entry. There are no sections, no wrappers, no dual-reads, no fallbacks.</p>

  <h2>Why the grammar is ours, not YAML's</h2>
  <p>A full YAML parser accepts a vast surface — anchors, tags, flow style, block scalars, implicit typing — and disagrees with itself across implementations. Each of those is a way for a manifest to parse into something other than what its author sees, and a head that silently mis-parses can drop a cell's hooks, skills, and provides out of the graph without a word (the incident that motivated the epoch: an unquoted <code>summary:</code> containing <code>: </code> once removed the constitution from every session). Epoch&nbsp;2 replaces the library with a <strong>strict subset</strong> the engine owns end to end, so that <em>the only way a head parses is the way it reads</em>, and anything outside the subset is a <strong>fatal error with line, column, and the fix</strong> — never a silent reinterpretation.</p>

  <h2>The head grammar</h2>
  <p>The head is a sequence of top-level <code>key: value</code> entries. A conforming parser MUST accept exactly the following and reject everything else.</p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Encoding</dt>
    <dd>UTF-8. Indentation is spaces only — a <strong>tab</strong> character in indentation is a fatal error (<code>tab character</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Keys</dt>
    <dd>A top-level key matches <code>[a-z][a-z0-9_-]*</code>. A nested key matches <code>[A-Za-z_./][A-Za-z0-9_.@/-]*</code> — dotted and mixed-case keys are real (environment-variable names, dotted config like <code>service.ARTIFACT</code>), and so are the graph maps' edge keys: capability names (<code>infra.compute</code>), pool refs with pins (<code>known.life/github@3.0.2</code>), and local-path refs (<code>./node</code>). A <strong>duplicate key</strong> at the same level is a fatal error (<code>duplicate key 'name'</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Scalars</dt>
    <dd>A scalar is a single-quoted string, a double-quoted string, or a plain string. <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> and <strong>integer</strong> literals are the <em>only</em> non-string types — there is no float, null-keyword, date, or other implicit type. A plain scalar that contains <code>:</code> is a fatal error (<code>plain scalar contains ':'</code>) with the fix to quote it: this is what makes <code>life: 1.0</code> the <em>string</em> <code>"1.0"</code> (decimals stay strings) and closes the Norway problem (<code>no</code>, <code>on</code>, <code>1.0</code> never coerce). Quote any scalar that carries a <code>:</code> or <code>#</code>.</dd>
    <dt>Empty values</dt>
    <dd>A <code>key:</code> with no value and no indented block is uniformly <code>null</code> — the "present, no config" edge (<code>infra.secret_store:</code>). A required string key (<code>name</code>, <code>summary</code>) left empty is a fatal error (<code>must be a string</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Block lists</dt>
    <dd>A key whose value is a list takes indented <code>- item</code> lines. Each item is a scalar or a one-line flat map. A map item written unquoted in a scalar list (<code>- cap: mode</code>) is the old flatten ambiguity and is rejected — quote it (<code>- "cap: mode"</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Block maps</dt>
    <dd>A key whose value is a map takes an indented block of nested <code>key: value</code> entries. Nesting is <strong>unbounded</strong> — a head is self-authored, not untrusted input; no depth cap exists to bump.</dd>
    <dt>Comments</dt>
    <dd><code>#</code> begins a comment to end of line. Comments are preserved by the migration codemod but carry no semantics.</dd>
    <dt>Forbidden</dt>
    <dd>Flow style (<code>&#123;…&#125;</code>/<code>[…]</code>), anchors/aliases/tags/directives (<code>&amp; * ! % @ `</code>), block scalars (<code>|</code>/<code>&gt;</code>), multi-document streams, and any implicit typing beyond the above are each a fatal error naming the offending construct and the fix.</dd>
  </dl>
  <p>Every rejection carries <code>file:line:col</code> and a one-line <code>fix:</code>. A head that does not parse does not silently degrade — its cell's contributions go inactive and the engine says so loudly.</p>

  <h2>The waist — the pre-gene bootstrap closure</h2>
  <p>The head's reserved keys are the <strong>waist</strong>: exactly what the engine must understand <em>before any gene is loaded</em> — identity, the dependency graph, and the session-contribution family it compiles from. The waist is closed; a conforming engine reads these keys directly. Every waist key is optional except <code>life</code>.</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>key</th><th>what it is</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>life</code></td><td>epoch marker. <code>1.0</code> selects this grammar; any other value (or its absence) is a fatal error naming the migration codemod.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>name</code></td><td>the cell/gene identity — pool slug and resource-name prefix.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>summary</code></td><td>the one-line description — the manifest's human-facing scalar, and the <em>only</em> descriptive field in the waist (the engine's own boot census / <code>status</code> / <code>ask</code> print it). Everything else a cell is <em>about</em> — icon, tags, and the publish fields — lives in <code>meta:</code> (below).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>imports</code></td><td>a map <code>&lt;ref&gt;: &lt;config&gt;</code> of named dependencies. The KEYS are the exact-pinnable dependency graph (install + minimal-version selection); each VALUE is that gene's config, opaque to the engine, handed whole to the named gene — in <em>every</em> cell that configures it, whether or not that cell installs it (a config-only entry is legal and ordinary).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>requires</code></td><td>a map <code>&lt;capability&gt;: &lt;config&gt;</code> of capability dependencies. A gene-satisfiable key resolves against the graph's <code>provides:</code>; an <code>infra.*</code> key resolves against the connected infrastructure adapter, and its value is that capability's <strong>provisioning config</strong> — the deployment manifest, grouped per capability. Invariant: a cell's config keys MUST be globally unique across its <code>infra.*</code> entries — consumers read one merged view (the unit is the cell: one deployment), so kind-prefixed names (<code>kv_title</code>, <code>db_name</code>, <code>bucket</code>) are load-bearing collision-guards.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>provides</code></td><td>a map <code>&lt;capability&gt;: &lt;config&gt;</code> of capabilities offered to the graph. The value is the <strong>provider's contract</strong> to that capability's consumers — e.g. an infra adapter gene declares its CI credential contract (<code>ci_env</code>, <code>ci_hydrate</code>) here, where the workflow generator already looks for providers.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>hooks</code></td><td>contributed lifecycle behaviour. Per-hook <code>priority</code> lives inside the spec.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>commands</code></td><td>contributed verbs. A <code>run:</code> MUST be <code>node &lt;file&gt;.js</code> — the dual-harness rule (below).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>skills</code></td><td>contributed skill directories (slash commands are skills).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>mcp</code></td><td>contributed MCP servers — portable across harnesses.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>contributed PATH directories (container harnesses; ignored by the shell-less isolate).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>tests</code> / <code>checks</code></td><td>the quality gates the engine itself runs — the publish gate and environment assertions.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>local</code></td><td>consumer-owned paths the vendor step MUST never clobber.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>inputs</code></td><td>values the install flow gathers before a gene is materialized — the definitional pre-gene read.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>shape</code></td><td>structural intent (<code>flat</code> marks an intentional accumulator) — read by the engine's own census.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>publishes</code></td><td>the pool gene this cell is the source of — read by the publish-drift probe.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>allow_local_imports</code></td><td>pre-publish exceptions to the register-first gate — an engine security rail.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>meta</code></td><td>the one non-waist top-level key: descriptive metadata (<code>icon</code>, <code>tags</code>, <code>description</code>, <code>author</code>, <code>license</code>, <code>homepage</code>, <code>repository</code>, <code>keywords</code>) — what a cell is <em>about</em>, read by the viewer chrome, the registry catalog, and the engine's publish path, never by composition. Descriptive metadata is substrate, not a peer gene.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Any other top-level key is a <strong>hard error</strong> naming the rule — gene config belongs under its <code>imports:</code> entry; capability and provisioning config belongs under its <code>requires:</code> entry. A cell carrying an illegal key <strong>deactivates</strong> — its own hooks, skills, and provides go inactive and <code>test</code> reds — but it is never removed from the graph: its <code>name</code> and <code>imports</code> stay visible, so a cold materialize can always install its dependencies. Per-gene and per-adapter config schemas are documented by their owning genes, not here: see the <a href="/docs/adapters/infrastructure">infrastructure</a>, <a href="/docs/adapters/harness">harness</a>, and <a href="/docs/adapters/storage">repo</a> adapter references.</p>

  <h2>One primitive, two readers</h2>
  <p>Composition ("another gene satisfies this") and provisioning ("adapter, make this exist in the world") are different speech acts — but they do not need different syntaxes, only clearly-owned <em>readers</em>. The engine reads only the map <strong>keys</strong>: <code>requires:</code> keys participate in graph resolution exactly like epoch-1's list items did. The resolved provider reads the <strong>value</strong>: for an <code>infra.*</code> key that is the infrastructure adapter, and the value is the provisioning manifest that used to be a separate <code>infra:</code> section. The infra capability vocabulary (<code>compute</code>, <code>kv</code>, <code>datastore</code>, <code>object_store</code>, <code>secret_store</code>, <code>route</code>, <code>ai</code>, …) is owned by the adapter contract and is deliberately <strong>not</strong> frozen into this spec until a second adapter proves it from outside — a waist is extracted from running implementations, never legislated.</p>

  <h2>The dual-harness rule</h2>
  <p>A <code>.life</code> is harness-agnostic: it compiles onto a container harness (Claude Code, Codex) and a shell-less Worker isolate alike. A <code>commands</code> or <code>hooks</code> <code>run:</code> that is not <code>node &lt;file&gt;.js</code> silently no-ops in the isolate, so it is a <strong>fatal parse error</strong>, not a lint. (<code>pre_tool</code> hooks, which guard a Bash tool the isolate does not have, are the one documented exception.) A bare <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> item in <code>tests:</code>/<code>checks:</code> is likewise fatal — it would type as a boolean and be skipped silently, a lying-green.</p>

  <h2>Epoch and migration</h2>
  <p>The engine parses <code>life: 1.0</code> heads only. There is <strong>no</strong> dual-read and no auto-migrate shim — a <code>life: 0.1</code> head (or a markerless one) is a hard error naming the one-shot verb <code>life codemod</code>, which rewrites a whole tree's heads to the sealed shape in place (comments preserved and travelling with moved keys, each output verified against this grammar before anything is written, idempotent — a sealed head is a byte-identical fixed point). The epoch-1 <em>list</em> forms of <code>imports:</code>/<code>requires:</code>/<code>provides:</code> and the top-level <code>infra:</code> section are rejected the same way, naming the codemod. Old pinned versions stay resolvable as archival bytes for old engines — total versioning means the flip strands nothing. From this epoch forward every registry publish is signed and the registry <strong>requires</strong> provenance (see the <a href="/docs/spec/registry-protocol">registry protocol</a>); the optional-signing phase never existed.</p>

  <h2>Conformance</h2>
  <p>An implementation conforms iff it produces the specified outcome for every fixture in the executable conformance suite (<code>conformance/run.mjs</code> — 20 fixture heads with expected exit codes and message patterns, run against the built engine), which is the machine oracle; this table is its human face.</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>head fixture</th><th>required outcome</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>life: 1.0</code> + <code>name</code> + <code>summary</code> alone</td><td><strong>accept</strong> — the smallest legal head</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>imports:</code> map with null, scalar, list, and map config values</td><td><strong>accept</strong> — config is opaque, any shape</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>requires:</code> map with capability keys; <code>infra.*</code> entries carrying provisioning config</td><td><strong>accept</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>provides:</code> map with a provider contract (<code>ci_env</code>, <code>ci_hydrate</code>)</td><td><strong>accept</strong></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a <code>meta:</code> section</td><td><strong>accept</strong>; rides the index opaque</td></tr>
      <tr><td>deep nesting (six-plus container levels)</td><td><strong>accept</strong> — no depth cap</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a <code>life: 0.1</code> head</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>pre-epoch head ('life: 0.1')</code>, names <code>life codemod</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>no <code>life:</code> marker</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>no 'life:' marker</code>, names <code>life codemod</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>the epoch-1 list form of <code>imports:</code> / <code>requires:</code> / <code>provides:</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — must be a map</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a top-level gene-name section (<code>github:</code>)</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — names the key and the <code>imports:</code> rule; the cell deactivates but is not dropped</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a top-level <code>infra:</code> section</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — provisioning config rides <code>requires: infra.*</code> entries</td></tr>
      <tr><td>any other unaddressed top-level key (<code>frobnicate:</code>)</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — only <code>meta:</code> is legal</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a plain <code>summary:</code> value containing <code>: </code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> at <code>line:col</code> — <code>plain scalar contains ':'</code> + quote fix</td></tr>
      <tr><td>an empty <code>name:</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>must be a string</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>flow style <code>meta: &#123;icon: rocket&#125;</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>flow style is outside the epoch-2 subset</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a block scalar / anchor / tab-indent / duplicate key</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — each names the construct at <code>line:col</code> with the fix</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a command <code>run:</code> that is not <code>node …</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>dual-harness law</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a <code>pre_tool</code> hook with a non-node <code>run:</code></td><td><strong>accept</strong> — the documented exception</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a bare <code>- true</code> in <code>tests:</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — would type as boolean and skip silently</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>A clean-room second implementation of the engine parser is expected to be validated against this set; it is the on-ramp, independent of the reference code.</p>
